IndoEuropeanLanguage(x) ::: x is an Indo-European language.
LanguageFamily(x) ::: x is a language family.
Related(x, y) ::: x is related to y.
Language(x) ::: x is a language.
BelongsToFamily(x, y) ::: language x belongs to language family y.
French(x) ::: x is French.
Spanish(x) ::: x is Spanish.
German(x) ::: x is German.
Basque(x) ::: x is Basque.

# Premises:
# Language definitions
Language(french)
Language(spanish)
Language(german)
Language(basque)

# Romance languages are a subset of Indo-European languages.
∀x (RomanceLanguage(x) → IndoEuropeanLanguage(x))

# The Romance languages form a language family.
# We will refer to this family with a constant `romance_family`.
LanguageFamily(romance_family)
∀x (RomanceLanguage(x) → BelongsToFamily(x, romance_family))

# All languages within the same language family are related to each other.
# This relation is reflexive and symmetric.
∀x (Related(x, x)) # All languages are related to themselves.
∀x ∀y (BelongsToFamily(x, y) ∧ BelongsToFamily(z, y) → Related(x, z)) # All languages in the same family are related.
∀x ∀y (Related(x, y) → Related(y, x)) # Relation is symmetric.

# French and Spanish are Romance languages.
RomanceLanguage(french)
RomanceLanguage(spanish)

# German is related to Spanish.
Related(german, spanish)

# Basque is not related to any other language, meaning it's only related to itself.
# This implies that Basque is a language.
∀x (Basque(x) → Language(x))
∀x (Basque(x) → Related(x, x)) # This is already covered by the general reflexive statement.
# Explicitly state Basque is not related to other known languages if they are not Basque.
∀x (Basque(x) → ∀y (Language(y) ∧ y ≠ x → ¬Related(x, y)))

# Conclusion:
¬RomanceLanguage(german)
